 "EC2.414": {
  "title": "Advanced Memory Circuits and Systems",
  "prerequisites": "Basic Electronics or Analog/Digital VLSI Design, Computer\nSystems Organization or Introduction to Processor Architecture.",
  "outcomes": "After completion of the course, the students should be able to -\nCO1. Quantify and trade off the core figures of merit of any memory — latency,\nbandwidth, density, energy per bit, retention, endurance, and error rate — and\nexplain how the memory hierarchy responds to these conflicting constraints.\nCO2. Analyze and size canonical bitcells (6T SRAM, 1T1C DRAM, floating-gate / charge-trap Flash)\nand reason about their stability, sensing, and scaling limits.\nCO3. Explain the device physics and circuit / system trade-offs of emerging non-volatile\nmemories (PCM, RRAM, MRAM, FeRAM / FeFET).\nCO4. Design and evaluate memory-system components — caches, controllers,\nscheduling, and address mapping — and reason about disaggregated and tiered\nmemory (CXL, persistent memory) and its system implications, using standard\nmodeling tools.\nCO5. Analyze why memory dominates AI / ML performance and energy, and evaluate\nnear-memory and compute-in-memory architectures, including their accuracy /\nefficiency trade-offs.\nCO6. Critically read primary research literature and propose, prototype, or evaluate a\nnovel memory idea.",
  "topics": "Module I — Foundations: The memory landscape and the “memory wall”; figures of\nmerit and the memory hierarchy; the MOSFET as switch and capacitor,\ncharge storage, retention and leakage; array organization (wordlines,\nbitlines, decoders), precharge / equalization and array efficiency; sensing\nand peripheral circuits (voltage- and current-mode sense amplifiers,\nreference generation, write drivers, signal margin).\nModule II — SRAM: The 6T cell — cross-coupled inverters, read / write / hold, static\nnoise margin and transistor sizing; SRAM arrays and peripherals; stability\nunder variability and scaling, half-select disturbs, read / write assist\ntechniques; alternative bitcells (8T / 10T, dual-port), near- / sub-threshold\nSRAM, and the SRAM scaling crisis.\nModule III — DRAM: The 1T1C cell, capacitor technologies, destructive read and charge\nsharing; DRAM array architecture, sense / restore, refresh, key timing\nparameters (tRCD, tRP, tRAS, tCAS) and the command protocol;\nstandards and interfaces (DDR / LPDDR / GDDR) and the DRAM PHY;\nscaling and 3D, RowHammer and reliability, HBM, and near-memory\nprocessing.\nModule IV — Non-Volatile Memory: Flash fundamentals (floating gate, tunneling, NOR\nvs. NAND, SLC / MLC / TLC / QLC); 3D NAND and SSD systems (FTL, wear\nleveling, garbage collection); resistive and magnetic memories (PCM,\nRRAM, MRAM); ferroelectric memories (FeRAM, FeFET), a comparative\nNVM analysis, selector devices, and the crossbar sneak-path problem.\nModule V — Memory Systems: Caches and the hierarchy (locality, associativity,\nreplacement, coherence, virtual memory / TLBs); memory controllers\n(request scheduling, address mapping, row-buffer management,\nfairness / QoS); signaling and persistent memory; disaggregated and\ncomposable memory (CXL, pooling and tiering, far memory).\nModule VI — Memory for AI / ML & Compute-in-Memory: The memory bottleneck in\nAI (arithmetic intensity and the roofline model, weights / activations /\noptimizer state / KV cache, HBM, quantization and sparsity); near-\nmemory and processing-in-memory; SRAM and digital compute-in-\nmemory; analog compute-in-memory with emerging devices (crossbars,\nADC / DAC cost, device non-idealities, hardware-aware training).\nModule VII — Frontiers & Synthesis: Memory test and design-for-test (March\nalgorithms, BIST), redundancy and repair; reliability (ECC families,\nchipkill); memory security (RowHammer, cold-boot, side channels,\nencryption); 3D / monolithic integration and advanced packaging\n(chiplets, hybrid bonding); research frontiers (photonic, DNA /\nmolecular, neuromorphic, cryogenic memory) and student project\npresentations.\nPreferred Textbooks :\n1. J. M. Rabaey, A. Chandrakasan & B. Nikolić, Digital Integrated Circuits: A\nDesign Perspective (memory and periphery chapters).\n2. N. Weste & D. Harris, CMOS VLSI Design: A Circuits and Systems Perspective\n(memory, datapath, and sensing).\n3. K. Itoh, VLSI Memory Chip Design (DRAM / SRAM circuit depth).\n4. B. Jacob, S. Ng & D. Wang, Memory Systems: Cache, DRAM, Disk (systems view).\n5. J. L. Hennessy & D. A. Patterson, Computer Architecture: A Quantitative Approach\n(memory hierarchy, roofline).",
  "references": "1. J. Brewer & M. Gill (eds.), Nonvolatile Memory Technologies with Emphasis on Flash.\n2. Survey papers on in-memory and near-memory computing and on resistive /\nanalog crossbar accelerators.\n3. Primary literature on RowHammer and DRAM reliability / security and its mitigations.\n4. Processing-in-memory architecture papers from the DRAM / HBM-PIM line of work.\n5. SRAM and digital compute-in-memory macro papers from recent solid-state-circuits venues.\n6. CXL and disaggregated / tiered-memory system papers.\n7. Vendor data sheets and JEDEC standards excerpts for DDR / LPDDR / HBM\n(read as engineering documents).\nConferences / journals to track: ISSCC, VLSI Symposia, IEDM (devices / circuits);\nISCA, MICRO, HPCA, ASPLOS (systems); DAC / ICCAD (design); and Nature\nElectronics / Nature Nanotechnology for emerging-device milestones.\nE-book Links : E-editions of the listed textbooks are accessible through the IIIT-H digital\nlibrary and the respective publisher platforms; survey and primary papers, conference proceedings,\nand standards excerpts are available via IEEE Xplore and the ACM Digital Library. (Specific institute-\nlicensed access links to be added by the instructor.)",
  "teaching": "The course is delivered through lectures and tutorials that build understanding bottom-\nup — from device and bitcell foundations to full memory subsystems and the compute-\nin-memory frontier. Each circuit-oriented topic is paired with a hands-on simulation lab\n(SPICE for bitcell, SNM, and sense-amp analysis; CACTI, NVSim, and DRAM / full-system\nsimulators for array and system studies) so that abstractions stay grounded in\nquantitative results. A single running thread revisits the same figures of merit —\nlatency, bandwidth, density, energy, and endurance — for every memory studied,\nhelping students build an internal comparison map rather than isolated facts. Primary\nresearch literature is read and critiqued throughout, with graduate students leading\npaper discussions, and a level-differentiated term project lets each student design,\nmodel, or prototype a memory idea at an appropriate depth. The difficulty and\nemphasis of modules are scaled to the audience mix, expanding the foundations or\ncompressing them in favour of seminar-style discussion of the advanced modules as\nthe cohort requires.\n-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------",
  "assessment": "Type of Evaluation Weightage (in %)\nQuiz-1 10\nMid Sem Exam 20\nQuiz-2 10\nEnd Sem Exam 20\nAssignments 10\nProject+Term Paper 30",
  "raw": null
 },
